'''د کلات خان''' یا '''Khan-e-Qalat''' ({{lang-bal|خان قلات}}) دا یو نوم دی چې د [[د کلات خانات|کلات د خاناتو]] د پخواني واکمنۍ د مشر لپاره کاریده. د کلات خانات اوس محال د پاکستان د  [[بلوچستان]] یوه برخه ده چې بلوچستان د ۱۹۴۸ د مارچ په ۳۰ د پاکستان لخوا اشغال شو.  The rulers in Kalat first were subjected to [[Mughal emperor]] [[Akbar]] in [[Delhi]]<ref>[http://www.uob.edu.pk/journals/TREATY%20OF%20KALAT%201758%20BETWEEN%20QANDHAR%20AND%20KALAT%20AND%20ITS%20IMPACTS.pdf Treaty of Kalat between Balochistan and Afghanistan in 1758]</ref><ref name="IG6-277">"Baluchistan" ''Imperial Gazetteer of India'' Vol. 6, [http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V06_283.gif p. 277], from the Digital South Asia Library, accessed 15 January 2009</ref> after 1839 to the British, and since 1948 to the [[Pakistani government]].

The rulers of Kalat held the title of [[Wāli|Vali]] originally but in 1739 they also took the title (Begler Begi) [[Khan (title)|Khan]], usually shortened to just Khan. The last Khan of Kalat was also the President of the Council of Rulers for the [[Baluchistan States Union]].

==مخېنه==
The Khans of Kalat belonged to  a [[Baloch people|Baloch]]<ref>Qambar gave his name to the Qambarani branch of the Baloch , just as Ahmed I gave his name to the Ahmedzai branch of the Qambrani, Balfour, Edward (1885) "India, Its Balochistan neighbours" ''The Cyclopædia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia, Commercial, Industrial and Scientific'' Vol. II H-NYSA (3rd ed.) Bernard Quaritch, London, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3U0OAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA195 p. 195], accessed 15 January 2009</ref> hill chieftain named Qambar (or Qumbar).<ref name="Keltie-1">Keltie, J. Scott (ed.) (1902) ''Statistical and historical annual of the states of the world for the year 1902'' Macmillan and Co., London [https://books.google.com/books?id=8_G23X69hdMC&pg=PA172 p. 172], accessed 15 January 2009</ref><ref name="Balfour">Balfour, Edward (1885) "India, Its Baluchistan neighbours" ''The Cyclopædia of India and of Eastern and Southern Asia, Commercial, Industrial and Scientific'' Vol. II H-NYSA (3rd ed.) Bernard Quaritch, London, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3U0OAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA191 p. 191], accessed 15 January 2009</ref>  His tribe was hired by Sehwa, the Raja of Kalat, a [[Hindustan|Hindu]] [[princely state]], to protect against marauding tribes from the [[Multan District|Multan]], [[Shikarpur District|Shikarpur]] and [[Upper Sind Frontier District|Upper Sind]] areas.<ref name="Balfour"/>  [[Mir Qambar Baloch]] and his troops successfully repressed the incursion, but afterward, they deposed the raja and Mir Qambar Baloch became the first Vali.<ref name="Keltie-1"/> 

